%N A350362 2-tone chromatic number of an n-cycle.
%C A350362 The 2-tone chromatic number of a graph G is the smallest number of colors for which G has a coloring where every vertex has two distinct colors, no adjacent vertices have a common color, and no pair of vertices at distance 2 have two common colors.
%C A350362 There is no 2-tone 5-coloring for cycles of length 3, 4, or 7 since the Petersen graph does not contain cycles of these lengths.
%H A350362 Allan Bickle and B. Phillips, <a href="https://allanbickle.files.wordpress.com/2016/05/ttonepaperb.pdf">t-Tone Colorings of Graphs</a>, Utilitas Math, 106 (2018) 85-102.
%H A350362 Allan Bickle, <a href="https://allanbickle.files.wordpress.com/2016/05/2tonejcpaper.pdf">2-Tone coloring of joins and products of graphs</a>, Congr. Numer. 217 (2013), 171-190.
%H A350362 N. Fonger, J. Goss, B. Phillips, and C. Segroves, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20220121030248/https://homepages.wmich.edu/~zhang/finalReport2.pdf">Math 6450: Final Report</a>, Group #2 Study Project, 2009.
